{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "NYISO generation interconnection application fee deposit milestone",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "NYISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "e265fb5b-5098-4f8a-8529-b45dfcab7939",
        "score": 0.6324293,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York, categorized by region and year (2018-2019). The chart shows costs in millions of dollars for New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports, with a total for each year. In 2019, the total was $52 million, down from $77 million in 2018. Long Island's costs remained stable at $15 million each year, with a significant portion (67%) attributed to high-cost peaking resources managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations include modeling specific constraints to improve market efficiency and reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_125.jpg",
          "page_num": 125,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a7d43ff1-4d13-404c-8b4b-0d2edc71769d",
        "score": 0.623369,
        "text": "The document discusses the reduction in total guarantee payment uplift costs, which fell by 32% from $77 million in 2018 to $52 million in 2019. This decrease was attributed to reduced supplemental commitments in New York City, lower gas prices, and decreased load levels during summer months. New York City accounted for $29 million (55%) of the BPCG in 2019, with over $21 million paid to generators for N-1-1 local requirements. Recommendations were made to adjust NYISO's local reserve requirements to improve efficiency. Long Island accounted for $15 million (28%) of BPCG, with nearly $10 million related to managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations were also made for modeling constraints in Long Island's markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_332.jpg",
          "page_num": 332,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ecdb3f8-11f2-4f49-a085-e78469e5814c",
        "score": 0.60726875,
        "text": "The document discusses \"Guarantee Payment Uplift Charges\" in the New York electricity market. These charges are used to recover additional payments not covered by Locational Based Marginal Prices (LBMPs) and other revenues. The charges are difficult to hedge and lack transparency, so minimizing them is crucial for efficient market operation.\n\nIn 2022, the total guarantee payment uplift was $94 million, a 74% increase from 2021, primarily due to higher gas prices and increased commitment costs for gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $50 million, or 53% of the total uplift, marking a 92% increase from 2021. A significant portion, over $36 million, was paid to generators committed for local reliability requirements. The document includes a figure showing uplift costs by region and category for 2021 and 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_102.jpg",
          "page_num": 102,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d2b0819e-2571-434a-ba00-aeaad8078ed6",
        "score": 0.6037033,
        "text": "The document page discusses the increase in uplift costs from guarantee payments in 2018. Key points include:\n\n- Total guarantee payment uplift rose by 102% from $38 million in 2017 to $77 million in 2018. This increase was due to higher supplemental commitments, out-of-market (OOM) levels, and increased natural gas prices affecting gas-fired units.\n\n- New York City accounted for $45 million of the BPCG (Balancing Payment for Capacity Guarantee) uplift in 2018. This included nearly $6 million from the Minimum Oil Burn requirements, where steam units used a blend of oil and gas, and over $26 million paid to generators for N-1-1 local requirements. Recommendations were made to model local reserve requirements to reduce BPCG uplift and improve price signals.\n\n- Nearly $10 million of BPCG uplift was related to high-cost peaking resources on Long Island, used to manage 69 kV congestion and local voltage needs. Recommendations were made to model 69 kV constraints and local voltage requirements on Long Island in market operations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_319.jpg",
          "page_num": 319,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2418dcc9-c47f-4f11-8e00-9e2963db9b4d",
        "score": 0.60116786,
        "text": "The document page discusses the uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York for the years 2016 and 2017. In 2017, the total uplift cost was $38 million, a 12% decrease from 2016's $43 million. The decline was mainly in Western New York, which saw a 49% reduction, and Long Island, with a 38% reduction. These reductions were due to less reliability commitment and out-of-market (OOM) dispatch. The local uplift in Western New York decreased significantly due to transmission upgrades and the expiration of the Milliken RSSA. The remaining local uplift could be eliminated if constraints were modeled in NYISO\u2019s day-ahead and real-time markets.\n\nAdditionally, the DAMAP, Min Oil Burn, and EDRP/SCR categories saw a reduction of over $5 million. Most uplift charges in 2016 occurred during high load days in July and August, which were not present in 2017 due to milder weather.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_109.jpg",
          "page_num": 109,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

